equation_narrative.headline: Charged surface context drives glutamate selection despite early hydrophobic representation
equation_narrative.story: Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation of position 16 by reading three structural contacts and local sequence context. The logit lens projects toward hydrophobic and polar residues (L, K, N peak at 22%, 16%, 13% respectively at L10-20), reflecting the mixed character of the immediate environment. This is not prediction—it's feature accumulation. The transition occurs at L23-24: attention begins writing charged-residue features, and MLP neurons activate prediction channels. By L30, glutamate-specific features dominate (F30:4067 projects 46.1 toward E), and E surges from 0.8% to 72.9% in a single layer via attention-driven writing. The final 57.4% confidence reflects competition from aspartate (22.6%) and glutamine (13.9%), both chemically similar alternatives.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 gather structural and sequence context. Three structural contacts provide local chemistry information, but no co-evolutionary signal arrives (0 coupled positions). Early features (F1:5480, F1:9146, both 45.3 proj) encode position identity and local sequence. By L9, the representation incorporates broader context (F9:5728 at 58.1 proj, F9:1281 at 53.4 proj). The logit lens shows frequent lead changes among hydrophobic (L, F, A), polar (S, N), and charged (K) residues through L22, reflecting the model's accumulation of mixed chemical signals rather than prediction attempts. At L17-20, asparagine peaks at 13.3% and lysine at 16.2%, consistent with the polar/charged character emerging in the representation.
perception_phase.context_character: By L23, the representation encodes a surface-exposed position with mixed local chemistry—hydrophobic neighbors (KTITL upstream, VEPSD downstream) but positioned for charged-residue placement. The three structural contacts provide limited constraint, and the absence of co-evolutionary signal suggests this position's identity is determined primarily by local sequence context rather than long-range functional coupling.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 3 residues within 8Å, providing local geometry but limited chemical constraint
Co-evolutionary signal: 0 coupled positions—no long-range functional constraints detected
L9 attention features: F9:5728 (58.1 proj), F9:1281 (53.4 proj) encode sequence context and position character
L18 features: F18:10167 (7.3 proj), F18:7263 (6.0 proj) show reduced projection as representation becomes more abstract

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes at L28-30. At L28, E briefly leads at 20.4% before dropping to threonine at L29 (25.2%). Layer 30 is decisive: attention head L31:17 writes 3.3 toward E, and F30:4067 (46.1 proj) activates—a strong glutamate-specific prediction channel. E surges to 72.9%, its peak probability. Layers 31-33 refine the distribution: MLP neurons in L31 (N31:4793 projects 1.6 toward E) and L32 (N32:3409 projects 1.56 toward E) consolidate the prediction, while aspartate and glutamine gain ground as chemically plausible alternatives, bringing final confidence to 57.4%.
decision_phase.transition: At L23-24, the representation shifts from context encoding to amino-acid-specific prediction. L23 shows V leading at 21.9% with low feature projections (F24:1922 at 9.8 proj). L24 MLP neurons activate prediction channels: N24:502 projects 0.46 toward E, N24:29 projects 0.40 toward E. The logit lens trajectory changes from frequent lead changes (16 changes in L1-23) to stable competition among chemically related candidates (E, D, Q).

candidates.narrative: Glutamate emerges decisively at L28-30. At L30, attention-driven writing (L31:17 head projects 3.3) and F30:4067 (46.1 proj) push E from 20.4% to 72.9% in one layer. This feature is a strong E-specific prediction channel. L31-32 MLP neurons consolidate: N31:4793 (1.6 proj toward E), N32:3409 (1.56 proj toward E, also votes for D at 1.05). The final 57.4% reflects competition from chemically similar D and Q, but E maintains dominance through the decision layers.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges L28, peaks L30 (72.9%), stabilizes L31-33
key_evidence: F30:4067 (attn, 46.1 proj)—glutamate-specific prediction channel activates at L30
L31:17 attention head writes 3.3 toward E via structural reading (12.9% structural attn)
N31:4793 (1.6 proj toward E)—strongest MLP writer in decision phase
N32:3409 (1.56 proj toward E)—consolidates prediction in final layers

candidates.narrative: Aspartate is the chemically closest alternative to glutamate (both negatively charged, D is one carbon shorter). It maintains 2-3% through L1-29, then surges in L30-33 alongside E. N32:1334 votes strongly for both D (1.26 proj) and E (1.21 proj), reflecting their chemical similarity. D peaks at 26.3% at L32, finishing at 22.6%. The model recognizes both as viable for this charged surface position, but E's longer sidechain is ultimately preferred.
key_evidence: N32:1334 (1.21 proj toward E, 1.26 toward D)—votes for both charged alternatives
N32:3409 (1.56 proj toward E, 1.05 toward D)—prefers E but recognizes D as viable
Chemical similarity to E drives late-stage competition

candidates.narrative: Glutamine is the polar analog of glutamate (same sidechain length, uncharged). It maintains 8-9% through L8-29, then rises to 13.9% in L30-33 as the model considers polar alternatives. N25:3604 votes for Q (0.46 proj) over E (0.40 proj) at L25, and N29:1982 projects 0.50 toward Q versus 0.59 toward E at L29. The model ultimately rejects Q in favor of the charged E, consistent with the surface-exposed context favoring charged over polar residues.
key_evidence: N25:3604 (0.46 proj toward Q, 0.40 toward E)—briefly favors polar alternative
N29:1982 (0.59 proj toward E, 0.50 toward Q)—charged wins over polar
Final 13.9% reflects Q as chemically plausible but suboptimal

candidates.narrative: Lysine peaks at 16.2% at L20, reflecting the charged character emerging in the representation during perception. This is NOT the model predicting K—it's the logit lens projecting a representation that has accumulated charged-residue features. K appears because the model is reading context that includes charged positions, not because it's guessing lysine. By L23, K drops to 1.7% as the representation becomes more specific, and it collapses to 0.9% in the decision phase as the model commits to negatively charged E over positively charged K.
key_evidence: L20 peak reflects charged-residue representation character, not prediction
N20:469 erases E (-0.18 proj) while voting for K (0.39 proj)—temporary charged-positive bias
Drops to 0.9% as model distinguishes negative (E, D) from positive (K) charge

candidates.narrative: Asparagine peaks at 13.3% at L17, when the representation is consistent with polar residues. This reflects the model reading polar context (local sequence includes T, S), not predicting N. The logit lens projects toward N because the accumulated features at L17 correlate with polar chemistry. By L23, N drops to 2.0% as the representation shifts toward charged character, and it finishes at 1.3% as the model commits to charged E over polar N.
key_evidence: L17 peak reflects polar representation character from local sequence context
N18:2405 writes toward E (0.31 proj) while erasing N—shift from polar to charged
Final 1.3% shows N rejected in favor of charged alternatives

turning_points.description: The perception-to-decision transition. L22-23 show the last major representation shifts: attention erases 4.2 and 3.6 respectively (key_velocity_events), clearing the hydrophobic/polar representation accumulated in L1-21. V briefly leads at 21.9% at L22, reflecting the hydrophobic component of the local sequence (KTITL_VEPSD). At L24, MLP neurons activate prediction channels: N24:502 (0.46 proj toward E), N24:29 (0.40 proj toward E). The logit lens trajectory changes from 16 lead changes in L1-23 to stable E/D/Q competition in L24-33.

The decisive commitment to glutamate. At L28, E leads at 20.4% but drops to T (25.2%) at L29 as N29:4973 erases 0.87 from E while voting for T (0.76 proj). L30 is the breakthrough: attention head L31:17 writes 3.3 toward E (12.9% structural attention), and F30:4067 activates with 46.1 projection—a strong E-specific prediction channel. E surges from 20.4% to 72.9%, its peak probability. This single-layer jump (Δ=52.5%) is the largest velocity event in the decision phase, driven by attention (7.68 delta) reading structural context and activating glutamate-specific features.

Refinement and competition. L31 MLP neurons consolidate E: N31:4793 projects 1.6 toward E (strongest writer), but also 1.43 toward Y and 1.33 toward I, showing some uncertainty. L31 attention erases 7.9 total (both attn and MLP contribute), pulling E down from 72.9% to 65.0%. L32-33 MLP neurons (N32:3409 at 1.56 proj, N32:1334 at 1.21 proj) push E back up while also supporting D (N32:1334 votes 1.26 for D). Final distribution: E 57.4%, D 22.6%, Q 13.9%—all chemically related, reflecting the model's recognition of multiple viable charged/polar options for this surface position.

deep_dives.label: Early features L1-9
deep_dives.caption: L1 features (F1:5480, F1:9146 at 45.3 proj) encode position identity and immediate sequence context. L9 features (F9:5728 at 58.1 proj, F9:1281 at 53.4 proj) show the representation incorporating broader structural context. These are perception-phase features—they encode what's here, not what should go here.

deep_dives.label: Mid-perception L18
deep_dives.caption: L18 shows reduced feature projections (F18:10167 at 7.3 proj, F18:7263 at 6.0 proj) as the representation becomes more abstract. The logit lens shows N peaking at 13.3% (L17) and K rising to 16.2% (L20), reflecting polar and charged character emerging from context accumulation, not prediction.

deep_dives.label: Transition features L24
deep_dives.caption: L24 marks the shift to prediction. Features F24:1922 (9.8 proj), F24:6629 (9.6 proj), F24:805 (9.5 proj) are the first amino-acid-specific prediction channels. Compare to L18's 7.3 max projection—L24 features are stronger and more specific.

deep_dives.label: Decision features L30
deep_dives.caption: F30:4067 (46.1 proj) is the key glutamate-specific prediction channel that drives E from 20.4% to 72.9% at L30. Also note F30:6682 (36.5 proj), F30:5040 (33.8 proj)—multiple strong features converge on E. This is where the model commits.

deep_dives.label: Final features L33
deep_dives.caption: L33 features (F33:6423 at 87.2 proj, F33:4166 at 86.1 proj) are the strongest in the entire trajectory, consolidating the E prediction. These are output-layer features that directly shape the final logits.

deep_dives.label: MLP neurons L29-32
deep_dives.caption: L29-32 MLP neurons cast the decisive votes. N29:1628 (0.61 proj toward E), N30:3282 (0.54 proj), N31:4793 (1.60 proj—strongest writer), N32:3409 (1.56 proj). Also note neurons voting for D (N32:1334 at 1.26 proj) and Q (N29:1982 at 0.50 proj), showing the model considers chemically similar alternatives.

deep_dives.label: Attention heads L30-32
deep_dives.caption: L31:17 (3.3 proj, 12.9% structural attn) is the key structural writer that triggers E's surge at L30. L32:18 (-2.3 proj, 10.2% structural attn) is a structural eraser that pulls E back down, allowing D and Q to compete. L32:13 (2.0 proj, 15.7% structural attn) writes back toward E in the final refinement.

deep_dives.label: Velocity events L28-30
deep_dives.caption: L30 shows the largest velocity event: +6.7 total delta (7.68 from attention, -0.97 from MLP). This is the decisive moment where attention reading structural context activates glutamate-specific features. L29 shows -2.3 delta (MLP-driven), briefly favoring T over E before L30's breakthrough.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts glutamate by assembling a surface-exposed, charged-residue context through L1-23, then activating glutamate-specific prediction channels at L28-30. The decisive evidence is F30:4067 (46.1 proj) and attention head L31:17 (3.3 proj via structural reading), which together drive E from 20.4% to 72.9% at L30. The final 57.4% confidence reflects competition from chemically similar aspartate (22.6%) and glutamine (13.9%), both viable for this position but ultimately less optimal than glutamate's negatively charged, long sidechain for the surface-exposed context.
